    <fr:title text="Hamel basis">Hamel basis</fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
    <fr:date>
      <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
      <fr:month>5</fr:month>
      <fr:day>26</fr:day>
    </fr:date>
    <fr:authors>
      <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
    </fr:authors>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
    <fr:p>A Hamel basis for a vector space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> is a subset <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}_{i \in  I}]]></fr:tex> of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[V]]></fr:tex> such that:</fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li>It is linearly independent: Any finite subset of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> is linearly independent</fr:li>
<fr:li>It spans the space: Every vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v \in  V]]></fr:tex> can be expressed as a <fr:em>finite</fr:em> linear combination of basis elements, i.e., <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v = \sum _{i \in  J} a_i e_i]]></fr:tex> for some finite index set <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[J \subset  I]]></fr:tex> and scalars <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_i]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
    <fr:p>The key distinction between a Hamel basis and other types of bases in functional analysis (such as an <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0027.xml" addr="FA-0027" title="Orthonormal Basis">orthonormal basis</fr:link> or <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0028.xml" addr="FA-0028" title="Schauder basis">Schauder basis</fr:link>) is that the linear combinations in a Hamel basis must be <fr:em>finite</fr:em>.</fr:p>
    <fr:p>Some important facts about Hamel bases:</fr:p>
    <fr:ul><fr:li>Every vector space has a Hamel basis (by Zorn's lemma or the Axiom of Choice)</fr:li>
<fr:li>For an infinite-dimensional Banach space, a Hamel basis is always uncountable</fr:li>
<fr:li>A Hamel basis for an infinite-dimensional Banach space is not useful for analysis because the expansion coefficients don't have nice continuity properties, and the basis elements don't form a convergent series</fr:li>
<fr:li>The standard basis <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_i\}]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {R}^n]]></fr:tex> or <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {C}^n]]></fr:tex> is both a Hamel basis and an orthonormal basis</fr:li></fr:ul>
  </fr:mainmatter>
