            <fr:title text="Schauder basis">Schauder basis</fr:title>
            <fr:taxon>Definition</fr:taxon>
            <fr:date>
              <fr:year>2025</fr:year>
              <fr:month>5</fr:month>
              <fr:day>26</fr:day>
            </fr:date>
            <fr:authors>
              <fr:author>Long Nguyen</fr:author>
            </fr:authors>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <fr:p>A Schauder basis for a Banach space <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> is a sequence of vectors <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n\}_{n=1}^{\infty }]]></fr:tex> in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> such that for every vector <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x \in  X]]></fr:tex>, there exists a unique sequence of scalars <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{a_n\}_{n=1}^{\infty }]]></fr:tex> such that:</fr:p>
            <fr:p>
              <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{n=1}^{\infty } a_n e_n]]></fr:tex>
            </fr:p>
            <fr:p>where the series converges in the norm of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>A Schauder basis differs from a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0025.xml" addr="FA-0025" title="Hamel basis">Hamel basis</fr:link> in that it allows for infinite (but convergent) linear combinations of basis elements, making it more suitable for the study of infinite-dimensional Banach spaces.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Every Schauder basis <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n\}]]></fr:tex> comes with a sequence of coordinate functionals <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\{e_n^*\}]]></fr:tex> in the <fr:link type="local" href="FA-001Q.xml" addr="FA-001Q" title="Dual space">dual space</fr:link> <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[X^*]]></fr:tex>, defined by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[e_n^*(x) = a_n]]></fr:tex>, where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[a_n]]></fr:tex> are the unique coefficients in the expansion <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[x = \sum _{n} a_n e_n]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
            <fr:p>Important properties of Schauder bases:</fr:p>
            <fr:ul><fr:li>A Banach space with a Schauder basis is always <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0026.xml" addr="FA-0026" title="Separable space">separable</fr:link></fr:li>
<fr:li>Not every separable Banach space has a Schauder basis (as proven by Per Enflo for certain spaces)</fr:li>
<fr:li>In a <fr:link type="local" href="FA-000U.xml" addr="FA-000U" title="Hilbert Space">Hilbert space</fr:link>, every <fr:link type="local" href="FA-0027.xml" addr="FA-0027" title="Orthonormal Basis">orthonormal basis</fr:link> is a Schauder basis</fr:li>
<fr:li>The standard examples of Schauder bases include the Haar system in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^p[0,1]]]></fr:tex> for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[1 \leq  p < \infty ]]></fr:tex> and the trigonometric system in <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[L^2[0,2\pi ]]]></fr:tex></fr:li></fr:ul>
          </fr:mainmatter>
          <fr:backmatter />
        </fr:tree>
      </fr:mainmatter>
      <fr:backmatter />
    </fr:tree>
